                  ) shows a sharp drop at some critical temperature (Tg) above which viscous deformation begins to dominate. The same plot for tanÎ´ shows a rise with temperature, reaching a maximum around Tg, after which it decreases. In thermoplastic polyurethanes the drop in Eâ and tanÎ´ are more pronounced as the polymer viscosity continues to decrease without a strong plateau until the polymer begins to melt. These thermal effects on properties will be discussed below in further detail.
